snippet.textDisplay:
Man... Sometimes Anthony confuses the absolute Hell outta me.
I love Mac's earlier stuff, don't get me wrong. But from 'GO:OD AM' thenceforth, his sound was f***ing FIRE! You could hear the maturity settling in quite comfortably in songs like 'Favorite Part', and 'Small Worlds'. The absolute poeticism and R&B production - for someone like Anthony, I woulda thought... What's not to like?
I'm beyond ecstatic that he loves the album, yes. But hell... It's miraculous compared to what you thought about the rest of his layer stuff.

snippet.textDisplay: That’s a really fair rating. I agree with your qualms about Surf, but I can’t say your take on That’s On Me convinced me! To me that track tacks on some much needed brightness to the rest of the album, even if the tone still trends to melancholic. It’s like a salt and vinegar chip that cuts through the richness of a fatty sandwich. It reminds me of some of the soft brightness that makes some Beatles albums really glow with hope. Still, fantastic review!
snippet.textOriginal: That’s a really fair rating. I agree with your qualms about Surf, but I can’t say your take on That’s On Me convinced me! To me that track tacks on some much needed brightness to the rest of the album, even if the tone still trends to melancholic. It’s like a salt and vinegar chip that cuts through the richness of a fatty sandwich. It reminds me of some of the soft brightness that makes some Beatles albums really glow with hope. Still, fantastic review!

snippet.textDisplay: Anybody calling him a “junkie” or blaming him for his addiction/death have gained absolutely nothing of substance from listening to this album (and even Swimming). Mac does a beautiful job of illustrating his mental state and crafted an extremely relatable and introspective album. If you can’t imagine his thoughts and pain, you’re just not listening. I’m so proud of you, Mac. Thank you and Rest In Peace.

snippet.textDisplay: I can't listen to "That's on Me" and not imagine the amount of guilt and self-doubt Mac must have felt throughout the development of his career. Since falling into his work later than most people, I dove into interviews and stories about Mac - his depression, his self-depreciating critical eye - and this song really exemplifies these feelings. I keep wishing Mac had truer friendships, better connections with people who really connected with his heart, which seemed to be deeply broken.

Since falling into his work later than most people, I dove into interviews and stories about Mac - his depression, his self-depreciating critical eye - and this song really exemplifies these feelings.
